---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
const pageDescription = "High-level methodology behind Scouting Grade's 2026 NFL Draft model: what data types are considered and how to interpret outputs.";
const collectionSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "CollectionPage",
  name: "NFL Draft Methodology",
  url: "https://scoutinggrade.com/nfl-draft-methodology",
  description: pageDescription,
  isPartOf: {
    "@type": "WebSite",
    name: "Scouting Grade",
    url: "https://scoutinggrade.com"
  }
};
---
<BaseLayout title="NFL Draft Methodology | Scouting Grade" description={pageDescription} collectionSchema={collectionSchema}>
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>How We Evaluate Prospects</h1>
    <p>Public high-level framework for reading the board, grades, and mock outputs.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="display:grid;gap:.8rem;">
    <article class="card">
      <h2 style="margin:0 0 .4rem;">1) Evidence Categories</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:.2rem 0;">
        We review multiple evidence buckets: college production context, athletic markers, role/trait translation signals,
        and external market context. We do not rely on any single source in isolation.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h2 style="margin:0 0 .4rem;">2) Grade vs Rank</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:.2rem 0;">
        <strong>Grade</strong> is player-quality signal. <strong>Rank</strong> is ordering after additional context checks.
        That means two players with close grades can still sort differently.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h2 style="margin:0 0 .4rem;">3) Mock Logic Philosophy</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:.2rem 0;">
        Mock outputs balance board value with team context and positional economics. We aim for realistic team classes while still
        allowing variance and upside outcomes.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h2 style="margin:0 0 .4rem;">4) Update Cadence</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:.2rem 0;">
        Public pages are refreshed in cycles as new data and news are incorporated. Check the weekly updates page for timestamps.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h2 style="margin:0 0 .4rem;">5) What Is Private</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:.2rem 0;">
        Proprietary feature engineering, exact weighting, and internal calibration logic are intentionally not published.
        This page is a reader guide, not a full system specification.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
